<p>&ldquo;Today is a victory for all Texans. The right to vote is central to our democracy,&rdquo; state party chairman <a href="https://www.texasdemocrats.org/media/breaking-judge-signals-texas-democratic-party-will-win-lawsuit-allowing-all-eligible-voters-the-opportunity-to-request-a-mail-in-ballot/">Gilberto Hinojosa said in a statement</a>. &ldquo;Voters should not have to choose between their lives or their right to vote.&rdquo;</p>
<p>But Texas Attorney General <a href="https://www.salon.com/2019/01/31/texas-officials-quietly-back-away-from-claims-of-widespread-voter-fraud-trump-wont-notice/">Ken Paxton</a>, a Republican, vowed to appeal the ruling, arguing that mail voting could lead to fraud. Many states <a href="https://www.kgw.com/article/news/politics/oregon-mail-in-voting-safe-coronavirus/283-68e295a4-f58e-4774-9e40-7048836b8774">rely heavily on mail-in ballots</a> and have had no significant issues with voter fraud. Five states already plan to run all-mail elections this year, and 28 other states allow voters to request a mail ballot for any reason. The <a href="https://www.brennancenter.org/our-work/research-reports/why-vote-mail-option-necessary">Brennan Center for Justice</a> found that the threat of voter fraud is &ldquo;infinitesimally small.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Paxton <a href="https://www.texasattorneygeneral.gov/news/releases/ag-paxton-voting-mail-because-disability-must-be-reserved-texans-suffering-actual-illness-or-medical">argued that the court</a> &ldquo;ignored the plain text of the Texas election code to allow perfectly healthy voters to take advantage of special protections made available to Texans with actual illness or disabilities.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;This unlawful expansion of mail-in voting will only serve to undermine the security and integrity of our elections and to facilitate fraud,&rdquo; Paxton said, pushing a debunked claim. &ldquo;Mail ballots based on disability are specifically reserved for those who are legitimately ill and cannot vote in-person without needing assistance or jeopardizing their health&hellip; My office will continue to defend Texas&rsquo;s election laws to ensure that our elections are fair and our democratic process is lawfully maintained.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;There is no evidence that voting by mail results in significant fraud,&rdquo; <a href="https://www.salon.com/2020/04/09/trump-says-he-only-gave-colorado-1-of-the-ventilators-it-needs-after-gop-senator-asked-for-them/">said a report from the Brennan Center</a>. &ldquo;Twenty-three percent of ballots were cast by mail in 2016, and twenty-six percent of ballots were cast by mail in 2018.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Paxton went even further earlier this week, <a href="https://lawandcrime.com/covid-19-pandemic/texas-ag-threatens-voting-rights-groups-with-felony-charges-for-pushing-vote-by-mail/">threatening to bring felony charges</a> against voting rights groups that promote mail voting.</p>
<p>&ldquo;To the extent that third parties advise voters to apply for a mail-in ballot based solely on fear of contracting Covid-19, such activity could subject those third parties to criminal sanctions,&rdquo; Paxton&rsquo;s office said in an advisory. &ldquo;However, whether specific activity constitutes an offense under these provisions will depend upon the facts and circumstances of each individual case.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Paxton&rsquo;s claims about voter fraud echoed those made by <a href="https://www.salon.com/2020/04/09/trump-babbles-an-incoherent-response-after-hes-cornered-by-reporter-over-mail-in-voting-hypocrisy_partner/">President Trump</a>, who has argued with no evidence that Democrats use mail ballots to &ldquo;cheat&rdquo; even though the only recent case of systemic mail ballot fraud was orchestrated by a <a href="https://www.salon.com/2019/07/31/gop-operative-indicted-for-n-c-election-fraud-now-charged-with-ballot-rigging-in-another-race/">North Carolina Republican operative</a> who was quickly prosecuted as the state held a re-do election.</p>
<p>Trump&rsquo;s comments came in defense of Wisconsin Republicans, who refused to allow an all-mail election and held an in-person primary earlier this month. Milwaukee, where the number of <a href="https://www.salon.com/2020/04/07/wisconsin-holds-primary-amid-pandemic-after-republicans-refuse-to-postpone-election/">voting locations was slashed from 180 to five</a> due to massive staff shortages, saw <a href="https://urbanmilwaukee.com/2020/04/07/milwaukee-reports-lower-than-expected-voter-turnout/">turnout plummet</a> as voters were forced to endure hours-long lines.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Our state is better off when more Texans participate in our democracy,&rdquo; Hinojosa said after Wednesday&rsquo;s decision. &ldquo;Voting by mail is safe, secure and accessible. It allows more voters to participate in our democracy, and it&rsquo;s a common sense way to run an election, especially during a public health crisis.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Anthony Gutierrez, the head of the watchdog group Common Cause, added that Paxton&rsquo;s threat to bring charges against voting rights groups put voters at risk.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Threatening to prosecute Texans who simply want to vote without endangering themselves, their families or their neighbors is just cruel,&rdquo; he told <em>The</em> <em>Dallas Morning News</em>. &ldquo;Everyone who works on voting rights or elections in Texas, including the secretary of state, has said this is a piece of law that is not clear, hence the litigation, and the judge made what we believe is the right call today.&rdquo;</p>
<div class="truth-post-content-after popmake-campaign-banners-popup  inline-callout-container" id="truth-255816"><aside class="popmake-campaign-banners-donate-modal  callout inline-callout callout--campaign callout--light" id="truth-270193">
